## Stereotype Annotations in Spring

---

### 🧠 What Are Stereotype Annotations?

Instead of manually defining every bean in `AppConfig.java` with `@Bean`, you mark your classes directly with **stereotype annotations** — Spring auto-detects them via **component scanning**.

```
@Bean in AppConfig.java     →  you manually register each bean
Stereotype Annotations      →  Spring auto-discovers beans itself
```

---

### 📌 The Stereotype Family

```
        @Component
        (parent of all)
             │
    ┌────────┼────────┐
    ▼        ▼        ▼
@Service  @Repository  @Controller/@RestController
```

| Annotation | Layer | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `@Component` | Any | Generic bean — doesn't belong to specific layer |
| `@Service` | Business Logic | Marks service layer classes |
| `@Repository` | Data Access | Marks DAO/repository classes |
| `@Controller` | Presentation | Handles HTTP, returns views (MVC) |
| `@RestController` | Presentation | `@Controller` + `@ResponseBody` — returns JSON |

> All 4 are technically the same to Spring — they all register a bean. The difference is **semantic** (readability + layer clarity) and some extras like exception translation in `@Repository`.

---

### 📌 How Auto-Detection Works

```java
// AppConfig.java
@Configuration
@ComponentScan(basePackages = "com.example")  // scan this package
public class AppConfig { }
```

Spring scans every class in `com.example` — if it finds any stereotype annotation, it **automatically registers that class as a bean**.

