### 📊 All Stereotype Annotations — Summary

| Annotation | Layer | Extra Behaviour |
|---|---|---|
| `@Component` | Any | Basic bean registration |
| `@Service` | Service | No extra — semantic clarity |
| `@Repository` | DAO | Translates DB exceptions to Spring's `DataAccessException` |
| `@Controller` | Web MVC | Works with `ViewResolver` to return HTML views |
| `@RestController` | REST API | Returns JSON/XML directly — `@Controller` + `@ResponseBody` |

---

### 📌 How Spring Boot Uses This

```java
@SpringBootApplication
// includes @ComponentScan — scans your main package + all sub-packages
public class MyApp {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(MyApp.class, args);
    }
}
```

> In Spring Boot you **never write** `@ComponentScan` manually — `@SpringBootApplication` already does it for the entire project. Just put your classes in the right package and annotate them.

---

### 🔑 Interview One-Liner
> "Stereotype annotations (`@Component`, `@Service`, `@Repository`, `@Controller`) mark classes for auto-detection by Spring's component scan — eliminating manual `@Bean` registration. They're semantically meaningful: `@Repository` adds DB exception translation, `@RestController` adds `@ResponseBody`. In Spring Boot, `@SpringBootApplication` enables component scanning automatically."
